{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17479976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17479976"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:35:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:35:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22264"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22264"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.18,0.06,0.04,0.68]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15229"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107858"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15229","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15229"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22264"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90278"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2780"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8888"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"40231"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40232"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44013"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107858","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107858"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with her parent with concerns about recurrent conjunctivitis. She has had chronic excessive tearing from the left eye for the past 12 months with intermittent episodes of mucopurulent discharge. The parent reports that the discharge is worse in the mornings. They have tried chloramphenicol eye drops from the pharmacy multiple times and lacrimal sac massage as advised by their maternal health nurse, with no improvement. The child has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She is up to date with immunisations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The left eye shows clear tears pooling in the lower fornix with some dried mucopurulent material at the medial canthus. The conjunctiva appears white and non-inflamed. There is no eyelid swelling or erythema. The right eye examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Topical antihistamine drops","Eye swab for chlamydia PCR","Oral azithromycin","Topical corticosteroid drops","Referral for nasolacrimal duct probing"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with classic features of nasolacrimal duct obstruction: unilateral epiphora (excessive tearing), recurrent mucopurulent discharge, and absence of conjunctival inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral for nasolacrimal duct probing\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management for this two-year-old child. While conservative management with lacrimal sac massage is first-line treatment for congenital nasolacrimal duct obstruction, this is typically successful only in infants under 12 months of age. For patients 12 months onwards with increased tearing that persists past 12 months of age, the approach is to treat medically (with lacrimal sac massage and topical antibiotics for secondary infection) and refer only if symptoms persist for more than three months. Referral should be non-urgent for nasolacrimal duct probing. Given that this child is two years old and has had symptoms for 12 months despite topical antibiotics, surgical intervention is now indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral azithromycin\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for chlamydial conjunctivitis, but this typically presents with conjunctival inflammation, follicles, and often bilateral involvement. The absence of conjunctival inflammation makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical antihistamine drops\u003C/strong\u003E would be used for allergic conjunctivitis, which typically presents with bilateral itchy, watery eyes with conjunctival injection and chemosis. The unilateral presentation and mucopurulent discharge are not consistent with allergic conjunctivitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEye swab for chlamydia PCR\u003C/strong\u003E would be considered if there was suspicion of chlamydial conjunctivitis. However, chlamydial infection typically causes conjunctival inflammation with follicles, which are not present in this case. The chronic tearing with intermittent discharge and lack of conjunctival inflammation points to a mechanical obstruction rather than infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical corticosteroid drops\u003C/strong\u003E have no role in the management of nasolacrimal duct obstruction and could potentially worsen any secondary infection. They would be indicated for severe allergic or inflammatory conditions of the eye, which are not present here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENasolacrimal duct obstruction occurs in approximately 6% of newborns. Most cases resolve spontaneously or with conservative management by 12 months of age. Probing is highly successful when performed between 12-24 months of age, with success rates exceeding 90%.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Nasolacrimal duct obstruction typically presents with epiphora and recurrent discharge without conjunctival inflammation.","Conservative management with lacrimal sac massage is first-line treatment for congenital nasolacrimal duct obstruction in children under 12 months.","Probing of the nasolacrimal duct is indicated when conservative management fails beyond 12 months of age."],"references":["Royal Children\u2019s Hospital Melbourne. Nasolacrimal duct obstruction: sticky and/or watery eye. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/kidsconnect/prereferral_guidelines/Nasolacrimal_duct_obstruction_sticky_andor_watery_eye/","Karti O, Karahan E, Acan D, Kusbeci T. The natural process of congenital nasolacrimal duct obstruction and effect of lacrimal sac massage. Int Ophthalmol. 2016;36(6):845\u2013849. Available at: https://doi.org/10.1007/s10792-016-0180-4"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90278"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22264"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90278","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90278"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-03T13:03:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-04T08:41:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15229"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107858"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{